data.content:
In .NET 11 / EF Core 11, the **sync-over-async opt-in for the Cosmos DB provider is removed entirely**. The configuration you had (e.g., `AllowSynchronousIO()` on the Cosmos options) no longer compiles or is ignored at runtime.

All synchronous LINQ operators — `ToList()`, `First()`, `Count()`, and `SaveChanges()` — will throw `InvalidOperationException` at runtime because the Cosmos SDK is async-only and EF Core no longer wraps it.

**Fix:** Convert to async equivalents:

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

This means async must propagate up through your call stack (controllers, services, etc.). There is no workaround — the blocking shim is gone.
